Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG?

Meenakshi Parameshwaran

4 February 2016

Executive Summary

I work for Motor Trend, a magazine about the automobile industry. In this project, I use the mtcars data set of a collection of cars to explore the relationship between a set of variables and miles per gallon (MPG) (outcome). I answer the following two questions:

  1. Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG?
  2. What is the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions?

Key findings

Methods

In the section below, I briefly explore the data.

Now I carry out some regression modelling to answer the two questions. In all models, miles per gallon is the outcome variable. The reference category for transmission type (base category) is automatic.

In the first model, I control just for transmission type. The model output shwos that, holding all else constant, transmission type is significantly associated with miles per gallon. A manual transmission gives an increase of 7.245 miles per gallon compared to an automatic transmission.

The first model’s diagnostic plot of residuals versus fitted values shows that three cars have high residuals and leverage: Toyota Corolla, Ford Pantera L, and Maseratic Bora. The Lotus Europa is close to being an outlier, with a relatively high dfbeta value for transmission type and also a high dffit value.

fit1 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = cars)
summary(fit1)
##

## lm(formula = mpg ~ am, data = cars)

# check model diagnostics
# influence.measures(fit1)
plot(fit1, which = 5) # there are three cars that have high leverage compared to their residuals

plot(fit1, which = 2) # QQ plot shows three outlier cars

plot(fit1, which = 4) # cook's distance

# create a new dataset that removes these three outliers
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
cars$carname <- row.names(cars)
cars$dfbeta_fit1 <- round(dfbetas(fit1)[,2],3) # get the dfbetas for transmission variable
summary(cars$dfbeta_fit1) # see the min and max of the dfbetas
##       Min.    1st Qu.     Median       Mean    3rd Qu.       Max. 
## -0.4680000 -0.1378000 -0.0125000  0.0000938  0.0967500  0.4750000
cars_no <- filter(cars, (cars$dfbeta_fit1 < 0.4 & cars$dfbeta_fit1 > -0.4)) # remove the outlier cases according to their extreme dfbeta values

The following two models repeat the analysis above, but with the three outliers removed. I futher control for number of cylinders and mean-centered car weights in the models.

# load packages for making the model table
library(memisc)

fit2 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = cars_no)
fit3 <- lm(mpg ~ am + factor(cyl), data = cars_no)
fit4 <- lm(mpg ~ am + factor(cyl) + I(wt - mean(wt)), data = cars_no)

mytable123 <- mtable('Model 1' = fit2,
                     'Model 2' = fit3,
                     'Model 3' = fit4,
